      <scopecontent id="aspace_a6bacbd2856d02bcf80a112acd36da4f">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The collection comprises pamphlets, newsletters, and other materials collected by Harry W. Selden and concerning conservative and right-wing politics and activism from the 1950s to the 1980s. Materials include newsletters, pamphlets, mass mailings, flyers, press clippings and photocopies, correspondence, and other printed and published materials. The material covers a wide range of topics, including the United Nations, disarmament, anti-communism, and Republican and conservative politics, and represents a large number of right-wing organizations. The collection also includes pamphlets and flyers for political candidates, primarily Republicans, along with a small number of newsletters and pamphlets from left-wing organizations. Some materials have handwritten notes and underlining by an unidentified author, possibly Selden. The collection also includes a partial inventory, possibly prepared in the 2010s.</p>  
      </scopecontent>
      <bioghist id="aspace_86aab558fda488f0534478708fe5b1a1">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>Harry Wythe Selden (1915-2003) was a Virginia farmer and John Birch Society member. Selden was born in Virginia on December 21, 1915 and worked on his family's dairy farm in Mathews County, Virginia (near Hampton) until 1947, when he moved to the Mechanicsville, Virginia area to farm. He returned to Hampton in 1991.
Selden was a lifetime member of the John Birch Society and served as its state coordinator and official spokesman. He was a frequent writer of letters to newspaper editorial pages and an active teacher and officer in local churches. Selden married twice and had two daughters and four step-children. He died in 2003.</p>  
      </bioghist>
      <accessrestrict id="aspace_4639b5f7da35bd4d3ed1d80d1061f723">
         <head>Conditions Governing Access</head>
         <p>The materials are open for research.</p>  
      </accessrestrict>
      <arrangement id="aspace_db0bd9cae6cde890612145a69880cb3a">
         <head>Arrangement</head>
         <p>The papers are arranged in five series: I. Pamphlets, newsletters, and other materials, circa 1950s-circa 1980s. II. Subject files, circa 1950s-circa 1980s. III. Correspondence, 1968-1969. IV. News clippings and reprints, 1959-1975. V. Ephemera, circa 1960s-circa 2010s.</p>  
      </arrangement>
      <userestrict id="aspace_4fb85d4381363d4f47a30bab23bc75c4">
         <head>Conditions Governing Use</head>
         <p>Copyright status for collection materials is unknown. Transmission or reproduction of materials protected by U.S. Copyright Law (Title 17, U.S.C.) beyond that allowed by fair use requires the written permission of the copyright owners. Works not in the public domain cannot be commercially exploited without permission of the copyright owners. Responsibility for any use rests exclusively with the user.</p>  
      </userestrict>
